Medical Report 

Patient: Mr. Wolfgang Ehrich, born on July 22, 1979, residing at Ahornweg 12, 10179 Berlin, 
patient number 456789, presented in our clinic during an acute flare-up of his known 
Crohn's Disease, which had previously been in remission. 

History:  
Mr. Ehrich reported an increase in abdominal pain, diarrhea, and occasional fever over the 
past few weeks. These symptoms are typical for an acute flare-up of his Crohn's Disease, 
which he has been suffering from for several years. 

Findings:  
A clinical examination and laboratory tests showed increased inflammatory markers. 
Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the intestinal tract confirmed active inflammation in 
the terminal ileum without signs of fistulas or abscesses. 

Diagnosis:  
Acute flare-up of known Crohn's Disease. 

Treatment:  
Mr. Ehrich was treated with an increased use of immunosuppressants, including the 
introduction of a TNF blocker to control inflammation and restore remission. Additionally, 
antidiarrheal medications and dietary advice were offered to alleviate his symptoms and 
improve his nutritional status. 

Follow-up:  
Regular appointments were scheduled to assess the effectiveness of the therapy and 
monitor disease activity. Adjustments to the medication will be made depending on 
response and tolerance. 

Recommendations:  
Mr. Ehrich is strongly advised to consistently continue the pharmacological therapy and 
regularly attend medical check-ups. Furthermore, he should adhere to dietary measures, 
especially during acute phases, to minimize symptoms and ensure adequate nutrient intake. 

Kind regards, 

Dr. Anna Müller
